[[File:United Kingdom on the globe (Bermuda special) (Americas centered).svg|thumb|Location of [[Bermuda]]]]
[[Bermuda]] is a [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] in the North Atlantic Ocean. It is approximately {{convert|1070|km|0|abbr=on}} east-southeast of [[Cape Hatteras]], [[North Carolina]]; {{convert|1236|km|0|abbr=on}} south of [[Cape Sable Island]], [[Nova Scotia]]; and {{convert|1578|km|0|abbr=on}} north of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]. The [[capital city]] is [[Hamilton, Bermuda|Hamilton]]. Bermuda is an associate member of [[Caribbean Community|CARICOM]].
Bermuda's economy is based on offshore [[insurance]] and [[reinsurance]], and [[tourism]], the two largest [[economic sector]]s.<ref name=Smithsonian>{{cite web |title=Bermuda – History and Heritage |date=6 November 2007 |work=Smithsonian|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/destination-hunter/bermuda-history-heritage.html |accessdate=3 December 2008}}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/player/nol/newsid_8330000/newsid_8339800/8339850.stm?bw=bb&;mp=wm&;news=1&;nol_storyid=8339850&;bbcws=1 "Bermuda's Tourism Industry"] Tayfun King, ''Fast Track'', BBC World News (3 November 2009).</ref> Bermuda had one of the world's highest [[GDP per capita]] for most of the 20th century<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rushe|first1=George|title=Bermuda|url=http://www.britannica.com/place/Bermuda|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref> and several years beyond. Recently, its economic status has been affected by the global recession.
A large number of foreign owned companies are [[Domicile (law)|domiciled]] in Bermuda due to its status as [[Offshore financial centre|tax haven]].
